segments.text: You want me to tell you who the people are?
Well, this is William H. Minkert.
And he came from St. Louis, Missouri.
And he was born in 1836 in St. Louis, Missouri.
And what did he do there?
Well, he lost both of his parents when he was real young.
And the story that I remember from it was that his father had some kind of store, some shop, merchandise there.
And when his father died, I don't know whether he didn't like his guardian or whoever it was, he just ran away.
And he was real young when he ran away.
I think early teens.
And I think that he, this is my belief, that I remember Daddy saying, is this too, am I talking too loud?
That's fine, that's fine.
That he came down the Mississippi, I think, river or along it, and he painted scenery and curtains and all kind of things.
things for opera houses and theaters.
Yes, it was a traveling show.
He did that.
That's how he earned his way.
On the Mississippi River, the boats too.
I thought he was coming down and maybe he'd stop at different cities.
Because back then, the rivers were the main form of transportation for industry and everything.
Most of the settlements stemmed away, branched off.
Daddy's dead, and I wanted a tape recorder when he was living.
I wanted to get all this.
Yes, my grandfather does the same thing.
He's deceased now, but we got some real, real tapes my mom got from him.
It's one Christmas Eve they spent, and it's really nice.
He was a poet.
He was a minister, and he used to write poetry, and every Christmas he'd send us poems.
Oh, well, isn't that wonderful?
And did he meet this girl?
Well, he came, and he was in Texas about five or six years, I think, or something like that, when the Civil War broke out.
And I've written it down on these, and you can have those if you want them to be verified.
If you don't want them, well, you know, go buy them.
But anyway, in February of 1961, Texas, he ceded from the union.
And he'd been here long enough that he used loyalties for the Texas.
So he entered the Civil War in September, or August.
It was August the 5th he went to the Civil War.
Let's see.
He met her then in Mississippi during the war.
Oh, yeah.
And so my sister has letters that he wrote.
He wrote very beautiful handwriting, and he told her, you know, that he wanted to marry her and that he'd come get her.
And we don't know how they got here, whether they came by train or, you know, that's what we'd like to know.
That's not in the letters.
Yeah, well, if... Or what?
Well, it could have been.
We think they probably came by stagecoach.
Yeah, that's a real good possibility.
Probably did because back then if they did come by boat down the Gulf, down the coast, Texas coast, I think that was rather expensive.
Yeah.
Well, anyway, he told her that if she would marry him, oh, they wrote each other.
They married in 1867.
They had a long courtship.
And he told her that if she would marry him, that he would take her little sister.
Her father had died, and he said he would accept her little sister as his own sister.
So her sister came, and her mother came.
I don't know exactly when they came, but he did do that.
And the sister then married a man who lived in Greenville.
So they came, yeah.
Let's see what else you'd like to know about him.
Did you happen to know what he did after he'd gotten married?
Yes.
Oh, he was a carpenter and a builder and like a, what do you call it, cabinet maker?
Yes.
But the main thing he did was he had a paint shop, and he painted the buggies.
And my daddy always said that...
Grandfather Minkert could paint buggies.
To be a buggy painter, you had to be the best of anything because people didn't want any lines ruined.
And you had to be a liner to paint a buggy.
You had to be perfect.
You couldn't make one mistake.
And Daddy did some of that.
He helped his daddy with it.
And he did that.
And then he, let's see, the courthouse before this one, and I've got it written in there,
He painted all the signs over the doors.
You know, they had glass transoms.
And he painted that, and one of my sisters has one of those when they tore it down.
I was over in Pakistan, so I didn't get one of them.
But his name was underneath the lettering, like whichever official it was.
So he did that, and my sister said he built the first house that was ever built in Brian.
Oh, do you know whereabouts it was?
Was it right near here, or...?
It's on Tabor.
Tabor Road, yes.
Tabor and 25th Street.
It's a corner of Tabor and 25th Street.
Do you know where the telephone office is?
I don't know the streets, but I know where Tabor and 25th Street are.
Do you know where the telephone office is across from the courthouse?
Yes, yes.
Well, this is at the opposite end where the telephone office is.
That's where that first house was.
And the first building, I guess it was a commercial building.
Well, at the time, I remember a building.
It was a huge, rambling building.
This was built after that.
And it was a bakery.
When you'd go in, the bell would ring, you know.
It was real cute.
And they had this wonderful smelling bread.
And Mother would send us to the bakery to get bread.
Well, my father also had a law office right there where the telephone office is now.
in the middle of that block.
The telephone company's office was right there on the corner toward the courthouse, and Dad's office was right next to it.
And then I've forgotten what was next to that, but I can't remember when the streets were paved, but there was a long time when we used a few.
You know, it wasn't too much paving even when I was in the sidewalks.
Well, how many...
children that Finney did this man have?
W.H.
Mitchell, he had five children that lived.
And here they are.
And I don't know that you'll want me to give their names, but this was my father.
And they had seven children, but five of them lived.
Two died in infancy.
What do you know?
Why is this stuff?
Many children died in infancy.
Yes, that's right.
With the measles or something like that.
They didn't have the technology.
And they'd have something they wouldn't even know.
Why?
I don't know.
I never did anything.
They just died in infancy.
But, you know, a lot of the undeveloped countries now, half of their children die.
I don't mean to be laughing at you.
Yeah, I like to say it's true.
The mortality rate is very high.
Yeah.
So...
Let's see what else he did now.
It's a book.
It's underlined in red.
Uh-huh.
Then, okay, Jesse Gardner Minkert was... Was my father.
Was your father.
And William Scott and Charles Aschel.
Ashel.
Ashel and Mary Hedman and Oscar.
Oscar, all lived.
They all lived.
I didn't give the names of those.
We have their graves out there in the Bryan Cemetery.
They all stayed in the Bryan area?
No, Daddy's the only one that stayed here.
What kind of, I don't guess you know why they left or anything.
Well, this one died as a young man, and he had something like William Scott died.
He had a grocery store in Greenville, I believe it was.
And he had something like, say, you'd say cholera.
It wasn't cholera, but some epidemic was going on.
Yes.
And he died in his early 20s.
They had cholera epidemics.
They had three different ones.
That wasn't what it was.
It was something like pneumonia or something.
I don't remember.
I know what it is.
My teacher's going to kill me for this because I can't remember right now.
We just did a big...
a big deal on the area.
We did a field trip a couple of weekends ago, and we traveled through the Brazos Valley.
Well, he died in about 1889, I guess, or 1890, because he was in his 20s, and Daddy said he had a grocery store.
And what about Charles, ain't you?
I think he was a carpenter, and he moved around.
He did come back to Brian when he was older.
He came back and lived with us.
And Mary Edna married a man and she was a teacher and she married a man and went to Corpus Christi and lived to be real old.
And Oscar went to Greenville and was a prayer nurse.
A prayer nurse.
So everyone was kind of a...
towards the handicrafts, you know, such as... Well, some.
She taught, and Daddy was a lawyer, and they used to rely to that.
Well, Mrs. Fletcher said that your dad was a judge.
Well, he was county attorney twice, I believe, and he was county surveyor twice, I believe, and county judge.
And I don't know how long he was county judge.
But in general, he just was a practicing attorney.
Did surveying around here, a lot of the surveying.
He studied law under his uncle?
His uncle was the man, his uncle was
Judge Montrose, and he was the man that this sister that my grandfather said he would take care of, she took each of his children into her home at some time to pay him back for caring for her.
And so she had my father there, and he studied law under this husband of hers.
And Edna lived with her a while, too.
I think some others did, too.
But anyway, they must have been a close family.
And Jesse was admitted to the Texas Bar at 18-6.
At the age of 22, that's...
He was real young at the time.
I think he was one of the youngest that was ever admitted for something somebody said.
I have here his...
Here's his write-up.
If there's any reason you need it to...
In writing this up, I don't know whether you'll care about it or not, when he died, they put that in the bar journal about him, you know, his career.
And here is his, I found this just recently.
You know, I was gone and things got thrown away.
We had books, and I think I found this in an old book.
Supreme Court, State of Texas.
He was...
license to practice on May 29, 1903.
Wow.
And we had this Brian Centennial in 1962.
Now, Hugh, I don't know how deep you're going into this, whether you're just writing something superficial or not.
But is this just for a theme, or what is it here?
Well, we're going to eventually arrow every student in all the sections.
and turn in their papers, and she's going to kind of get together, you know, I guess a book of the history of Bryan College Station.
Here was in the centennial in 1962.
That's right up there.
Some of the early ones were written up at that time.
Oh, yeah.
You can take that if you want to.
Some of it may duplicate.
If you don't want to do it, it's all right.
And this gives Daddy's.
It says here, and I didn't realize that.
I was overseas when Daddy died.
It said he was reportedly the oldest living native resident, the oldest barn resident.
And where did that?
He lived here.
We lived here always.
Except I've moved off and come back.
Did he live, I mean... Oh, what house did he live in?
Was it near here?
Oh, I've got a picture in here.
Oh, that's where we lived when I was born.
It was on 29th and Parker, I believe is the name of that street.
This is our family.
So the center of the city has...
It changed.
This house is where I was born.
I've been trying to just... Just lately, I'm just sticking these pictures in here and I want to come up.
And this house has been torn down.
I went over to show somebody the house and they were tearing it down.
And it's on the corner across the street from St. Anthony Catholic Church and it's on 29th Street.
208 29th Street was where it was.
then as Daddy and Mother lived in this house at the time Mother died and Daddy died.
That's their home.
It's over on the east side.
And that's on 24th Street.
What was the main type of work that was common in Bryan at that time?
Was it a lot of farming?
I think it was mostly farming.
I know cotton was pretty prevalent in the Branson Valley area.
Yeah, well, if you're studying that, you might know more about that than I do.
I was just curious.
They had their different stores, you know, the merchants.
They had the bars and the restaurants.
They had the restaurants.
The main road of travel used to be on, you know, not Texas, but Collins.
Oh, yes.
Until they built Highway 6, right?

I asked my sister today, I said, now, my first memory of the population of Bryan was I heard, the first time I remember anybody saying how many people lived in Bryan, and I don't remember what year that was, but they said, Bryan is getting so big, it has 8,000 people in it,
And that number stuck with me because I thought, oh, that's many people.
And I said, now, what is the first time you've heard of the population?
And she said, well, somebody said that Ron had 2,500 people.
And they says, oh, you're bragging.
So she remembers.
She's eight years older than I am.
If you think about 8,000 people and everybody had a family of three to five or ten children, everybody had a big family that we knew.
And there would be five in the family anyway with a father and mother.
Well, that made about 4,000 families and you just about knew everybody even when I was growing up.
You knew almost everybody in town.
You knew the families.
You heard of them or you knew them.
So you pretty well knew what was going on all the time.
Yeah.
That's really interesting.
Do you remember anything about the flooding of the Brazos River back then or anything like that?
Mother, I was born in the middle of a flood.
And I wasn't born in the middle of the flood.
I was born during the flood of 1913.
Have you all studied that flood of 1913?
Yes, we have.

Well, Mother has written down somewhere that I was born during that flood, and she always told me that, and said it was a terrible storm and everything, and there was a girl my age that was born, Mary Cavett was born during the time, and her father was in the flood, and from exposure he died.
And so she never did know her father.
And I remember there weren't too many cases like that, you know, and I always thought how terrible that was.
Was there a lot of blacks in the area back then, in the Bryan Constitution area?
Oh, yes.
I was just talking to these other people in our class, and they said they interviewed some people, and they mentioned something about how
Certain times of the day, the white people didn't even walk around the Brian Cox station outside because that was when all the black people came into town and all this other stuff.
Did you know that?
It was a lot safer to walk in than it is now, to be sure.
Yeah.
But I think my sister told me this morning, she said down at a certain part in Main Street, down that lower part, she said they did come to town on Saturday.
Now, that agrees with what you said.
And she said, nobody would go out down that part of town.
And I've forgotten on Saturdays, I do remember how full town would get.
Everybody would come to town.
And that hasn't been, within about 20 years, they stopped doing that on Saturdays.
That was a big day.
Was there a, I know the railroad goes through Brine, did a...
Do you remember, or your parents or anybody ever saying about how it used to be before the railroad and after the railroad or the effects or anything like that?
No, I didn't hear anything about that.
Because, you know, a lot of towns back then, their existence depended on, you know, where the railroad went.
Oh, yes, that's right.
Well, of course, the railroad was...
Brian took the, let it stop here, and that's why Brian grew another, you've heard that, you've read that too, that's why Brian, instead of Millicent, became a big team.
Right, right.
Yeah.
And then my other grandparents who came in 1893, my mother's parents, came by railroad, and...
Their older son had come to this community, or close to this community, and he liked Texas and had been here several years.
Who's this now?
My mother's.
Your mother's son.
They came in 1893, which isn't too recently.
And mother, my grandfather, McClellan, my father's father-in-law,
decided to bring his whole family.
So they came, they sold everything.
What drew them to the area?
Well, their son had come over here and bought a farm.
And he evidently convinced them to come to Texas, too.
Now, this is something.
He had nine children.
He had one daughter who was married, and she and her husband came with them.
Or at least if they didn't come in, they came right afterwards.
But he brought all these children, and the mother was 13, and she said that she was
really afraid because she'd heard how wild the Texans were.
You know, they're still telling that on us.
And she said that she'd come through, people would come through looking just wild on the train and they'd say, that's a Texan.
And I'd say, be careful because that's a Texan.
And so Mother said she really was afraid and said she got here and of course married one of them.
Well, did they send their son to do them out here?
Yes, uh-huh.
Well, you know,
What had they done back east?
Well, my grandfather was a preacher.
He was a preacher.
I guess preachers could move around better than other people.
What was the basic religion?
Was there any one major religion?
I don't know.
I think we've had almost all of them.
He was a Baptist.
Both of my parents were Baptists.
There were a good many Baptists.
Grandfather McClung and his wife brought their organ with them.
Maybe it was because he was a preacher they did that.
But they brought that.
And my sister said that they ate off of the box that crated the organ until they could make them a table.
Was wood very hard?
No, I don't guess wood was very hard to come by.
No, there was plenty of wood.
I heard that there used to be a lot of cedar around this area.
Did you ever hear of that?
Yeah.
Oh, there was a lot.
Even until, you know, recent years.
It sure was.
And all this, see this house, where this house is, was a pasture when I was a girl.
All this area over here with fields and pastures.
And I was thinking the other day, you know, after you told me,
You think about things that happened.
Of course, what I'm saying isn't anything that far back.
But it would say it'd be 50 years ago, which is pretty far back.
That I would remember.
And I remember all these.
There wasn't any such thing as a postage sign, you know.
And people didn't care if you wandered around in their pastures.
And kids just roamed around and had a good time.
And we'd ask people if we could have their grapes or their dewberries.
We'd go in big groups, you know.
And it was wonderful.
It was pretty rural when we, you know, for a long time.
Did Bryan expand this way?
Oh, yeah.
Or instead of not that way, but towards College Station area?
No, first it expanded east and then toward College.
When did they first really start recognizing College Station as a separate little town?
Was it very noticeable back then?
Oh, it was always a separate town since I can remember.
Did it basically center around A&M like it does now?
No, I don't think so.
There were always people from A&M that came to church in Brownville.
There have always been communication and friendships between them.
Some people like to act like there's a
You know, there's competition and all that, but there's always been as many friendships as there were competition.
Oh, just checking the tape here.
Let's see.
Is there anything you want to ask me?
Oh, just, you know, just basically, you know, just things about the area, you know, that happened, that might have happened to you, you know, while you were growing up, anything that really...
stands out in your mind.
Well, this is within recent years, but do you want mostly those things back there during my grandfather's day?
Is that what you want?
Is that what you're trying to get, those things?
I'm trying to get just about everything I can.
What do you know about it?
Well, Bryan was the place that the Hoods Brigade met.
You've probably heard that before.
They met here.
had their reunions here.
I've forgotten what, I've got the book on that, for quite a few years and this was the big event in Ryan.
Nothing could match that for, it was just gala, you know.
We just, for about three or four days, they just put it, rolled out the red carpet and these old veterans came and they closed the, you know, even that block on Texas Avenue where the courthouse is,
they'd close that and close all around some, maybe two blocks.
And they'd have speeches and singing and dancing and entertain these little old men that just barely could make it, you know?
So there's a man that has written a book just recently about the reunion of the Hoods Brigade, and he came to Brian and asked us to tell anything we could remember, you know?
So I said, well...
I go home, I think I've got something in the diary.
So I did, and he says, yeah, that he wanted to use that.
And I wrote that, and as soon as I read what I had written, well, I remembered it.
I said, there were two old slaves that came, you know, and everybody said, those are slaves.
And he said, well, that was the first time he'd ever heard of that.
Well, it may not have been slaves.
It may have been that they were Southern soldiers, you know.
Maybe that's why they didn't name them.
But they came with the veterans.
So that was interesting to me.
And he said that was the first time anybody had mentioned that.
But I know I wouldn't have said it if it hadn't been written, because I'd written it in 1933.
Oh, yeah.
Well, how often did they have these ?
Every year.
Once a year?
And this was 1934 was the last year.
I had written it in 1933, so he said that he was interested in that.
Do you remember anything about the impact of any of the, you know, country-wide conflicts or anything, how the impact it had on the Bryan Confliction?
Like, you know, World War I and stuff like that.
World War I?
I can remember the end of World War I. I was about four, let's see, I was about five.
And I was the only one in the family that didn't get to march in the parade.
And I was so humiliated because I had four brothers and sisters and they marched with flags in the parade.
down Main Street or wherever it was.
And I was too little, of course.
Now they'd let somebody that young in.
But I got to watch them anyway.
But I remember that part of it.
They said that they used to tell the joke on me that I was crying.
They were talking about the wars they were doing for the kids and I was crying.
And Mother said, what's the matter?
And I said, well,
All the boys are going to war, and then isn't going to be anybody left for me to marry except Daddy, and you've already married him.
So you don't put that in there.
But anyway, I do remember it.
Yeah, because a lot of times I break awards and stuff.
Like I'm from San Antonio, and before that I lived in Monterey, Mexico.
And I noticed when I was little that
Although my parents knew what was going on, political life.
I was a little kid.
I didn't know anything about it.
It's really strange because... Well, we had a hard time in the First World War and the Second World War.
There were many restrictions.
You want to turn that over?
No, that's just...
There were many...
Necessities, almost, that you did without.
And even as a child, I remember that.
And I remember there was somebody lived in a small house.
You know this house in the picture I showed you?
Yeah.
Somebody lived in a small house back of us.
And they sang this song.
And even though I was just about four years old, I remembered it.
And we'd sing that a long time.
It said, "'Eat bologna sausage till the bacon goes down.'"
That was some song, and we'd get tickled.
So I thought that was funny.
And everybody had a hard time financially.
Yeah.
What about the Depression hit you pretty good, too?
Here?
Uh-huh.
Oh, yeah, terrible.
Because I know back then, it was basically, was it still a farming community back then?
Were your parents in Mexico then?
No, they just been there since 1950.
But, you know, this was basically a farming community back then, wasn't it?
World War II, World War II.
So I guess it hit pretty hard.
Yeah, there were many, a lot of rationing and everything.
You've probably heard about that.
Do you remember the first time they ever paved the streets in Brine?
I noticed it back then.
Back, you know, whenever it rained, you know, a lot of cities were always in the mud.
I do remember as they paved a little at a time, you know, a little at a time.
And this Haswell Drive was...
I graduated from high school in 1931, and Haswell Drive, part of it, just part of it has been paved since we bought this house.
But the park that I went to walk to school on was paved in 1931, if I remember right, about the time because it was so muddy.
And we...
walked to school in mud all the time.
Didn't think about it.
Nobody rode to school.
That was more fun than riding because the whole neighborhood went like 20 or 25 together.
You just pick up another family, you know, as you go along.
That was the most fun.
I thought the children miss a lot because we had so much fun visiting and, you know, talking to each other and getting acquainted.
What was I going to say?
I thought of something.
About the paving.
And I guess they'll tell you we had horse troughs, and I can't remember when they took those horse troughs out of Main Street, but I remember them being there at the corners.
Right, yeah.
I think it's about the end of this tape there.
